Exercise 1:

arbuthnot$girls

Exercise 2:

As you can see in the plot below, the number of girls steadily rose over time, though there was a period from 1640 to 1660 when there was a notable drop in baptisms.

qplot(x = year, y = girls, data = arbuthnot, geom = "line")

Exercise 3:

The plot above shows that the proportion of boys varied year to year but stayed consistently above .5. It should be noted that though the counts appear highly variable year to year, the y-axis shows that the changes are actually quite small.

On your own:

1:

dim(present)
## [1] 63  3
names(present)
## [1] "year"  "boys"  "girls"

By viewing the present data set, we can see that it has data from 1940 - 2010. The dimension are 63 rows and 3 columns. The columns are the same as in the arbuthnot data set: year, boys, and girls.

2:

These counts are several orders of magnitude larger than those in arbuthnot.

3:

present <- mutate(present, total = boys + girls)
present <- mutate(present, boy_ratio = boys / total)
qplot(x = year, y = boy_ratio, data = present, geom = "line")

The plot above shows that there as been a gradual decline in proportion of births that are boys, with the exception of an uptick in the 1960s. Again, the scale on the y-axes is quite zoomed in, so the variation is exaggerated. Similar to arbuthnot, the proportion is consistently above .5.
